Bellabeat Analysis

Kasper KurzyÅ„ski

maj 2022

Ask

About the company

Bellabeat is a wellness Company headquartered in San Francisco that develops wearable computers for women. The company has offices in Zagreb, San Francisco and London. It was founded in 2013 by Sandro Mur and UrÅ¡ka SrÅ¡en.

Key Stakeholders

  • UrÅ¡ka SrÅ¡en: Cofounder and Chief Creative Officer
  • Sando Mur: Cofounder and Mathematician

Business task

Identify trends in how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices to apply insights into Bellabeatâ€™s marketing strategy. The company want to find answers to particular questions:

  • What are some trends in smart device usage?
  • How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  • How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Prepare

About datasets

  • The data source used for our case study is FitBit Fitness Tracker Data. This dataset is stored in Kaggle and was made available through Mobius.
  • Datasets were generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016.
  • Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. Consists of 30 users within a 30 day period from 2016.
  • Number of observations in the sample makes the sample size too small for proper analysis because there is a risk of sampling bias. There is also no demographic information to ensure that the data is representative of female users as Bellabeatâ€™s target audience.
  • Datasets are also not current and outdated, which may generate another problem in credibility.
  • There are provided 18 CSV documents. Each document represents different quantitative data tracked by Fitbit. The data is considered long since each row is one time point per subject, so each subject will have data in multiple rows. Every user has a unique ID and different rows since data is tracked by day and time.

Process

Also, from all 18 datasets I selected 3 of them, because in my opinion they can provide most useful informations to analyze trends and answer business questions.

Datasets for analysis:

final_data <- merge_data %>%
  select(-c("log_id", "is_manual_report", "weight_pounds",

         day_sleep = day.y) %>%
  mutate(day_activity = factor(day_activity),
         day_sleep = factor(day_sleep))

final_data$id <- as.factor(final_data$id)

Analyze & Share

Checking the assumptions about the normality of the distribution

Variables: total_steps, calories, total_time_in_bed and total_minutes_asleep donâ€™t have normal distrubution. Such conclusion can be made of the basis of the p-value in the shapiro.wilk test. For this reason, the Spearman coefficient will be used to calculate the correlation, while in the case of a median comparison between the groups, the Kruskal Wallis test will be conducted.

scoreShapiroSteps <- shapiro.test(final_data$total_steps)
print(scoreShapiroSteps)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  final_data$total_steps
## W = 0.9619, p-value = 6.079e-15
scoreShapiroCalories <- shapiro.test(final_data$calories)
print(scoreShapiroCalories)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  final_data$calories
## W = 0.96968, p-value = 4.336e-13
scoreShapiroBed <- shapiro.test(final_data$total_time_in_bed)
print(scoreShapiroBed)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  final_data$total_time_in_bed
## W = 0.91406, p-value = 1.608e-14
scoreShapiroAsleep <- shapiro.test(final_data$total_minutes_asleep)
print(scoreShapiroAsleep)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  final_data$total_minutes_asleep
## W = 0.95162, p-value = 2.48e-10

Scatter plots

According to scatter plots, we can observe positive and statistically significant correlations between variables calories and total_steps and total_minutes_asleep and total_time_in_bed.

ggscatter(final_data, x = "total_steps", y = "calories",
          conf.int = TRUE,
          add = "reg.line",
          color = "deepskyblue2") + stat_cor(method = "spearman") 

ggscatter(final_data, x = "total_time_in_bed", y = "total_minutes_asleep",
          conf.int = TRUE,

Bar plot

On this bar plot you can see that the highest percentage of participantsâ€™ daily activity is sedentary or light activity. High activity accounted for less than 2% of the total activity

sumMin <- final_data %>% 
  select(very_active_minutes, 
         fairly_active_minutes, 
         lightly_active_minutes, 
         sedentary_minutes) %>% 
  summarise(across(everything(), list(sum))) %>% 
  gather(active_level, minutes) %>% 
  mutate(active_level = factor(active_level, 
                               labels = c('Moderate Activity','Light Activity',
                                          'Sedentary','Heavy Activity'))) %>%
  mutate(percentage = percent(round(minutes / sum(minutes),3)))


ggbarplot(sumMin, x = "active_level", y = "minutes",
          color = "active_level", fill = "active_level", palette = "Set3",
          label = c("1.7%", "1.1%", "15.8%", "81.3%"), lab.col = "black", x.text.angle = 45)

The second graph shows what percentage of the total distance was represented by the participantsâ€™ activity levels.

sumDist <- final_data %>% 
  select(very_active_distance, 
         moderately_active_distance, 
         light_active_distance) %>% 
  summarise(across(everything(), list(sum))) %>% 
  gather(dist_level, distance) %>% 
  mutate(dist_level = factor(dist_level, 
                               labels = c('Light Activity', 'Moderate Activity', 'Heavy Activity'))) %>%
  mutate(percentage = percent(round(distance / sum(distance),3)))

ggbarplot(sumDist, x = "dist_level", y = "distance",
          color = "dist_level", fill = "dist_level", palette = "PiYg",
          label = c("28%", "10%", "62%"), lab.col = "black", x.text.angle = 45)

On the basis of the above data and graphs, certain conclusions can be drawn.

Conclusions:

  • If users want to lose weight, itâ€™s probably a good idea to control daily calorie consumption and impoving daily activity. Bellabeat should add notifications to control both values.
  • To improve users sleep, Bellabeat should consider using app notifications to go to bed.
  • Adding notifications to remind users to do more steps daily.
